Airiti Library華藝線上圖書館





































													篇名
												


臺灣當代男同志散文研究






														並列篇名
													


															A Study on Gay Essays in Contemporary Taiwan
														




														作者
													


															李東霖

														




													關鍵字
												



														臺灣當代 ； 男同志散文 ； 認同 ； 慾望 ； 慰藉 ； contemporary Taiwan ； gay essay ； identity ； desire ； consolation
													




													出版品名稱
												


														國立臺北教育大學語文與創作學系學位論文
													




													捲期/出版年月
												


碩士													




														學位類別
													

碩士




														指導教授
													

陳俊榮




													內容語文
												

繁體中文




														中文摘要
													

本研究旨在對臺灣當代男同志散文的內涵進行探究，分別從男同志散文書寫的性別認同、慾望參與，以及想像寄託作觀察，欣賞其中的美麗與哀愁。
　　在性別認同上，男同志散文的認同可以分作三個階段，首先是對性別意識加以召喚，其次是同志身分出櫃卅現身的考量，最後則是去除汙名標籤的實踐。它們除了對異性戀陽具中心與生殖主義的思想作出批判，也在散文書寫中主張同志族群應有挺身的勇氣，在大社會之中找到自己的位置。此外，社會對於同志的許多誤解，日積月累形成瞭如影隨形的汙名。不過，汙名標籤的書寫及辯護，在男同志散文裡頭其實不多見，話題也僅集中在變裝與愛滋上頭。臺灣當代男同志散文書寫的性別認同，展現的是一種面對同志的態度，只有到了同志都能不必被凸顯其同志身分而能夠享受自己所想要的性特質與性慾望時，這個社會才足以稱為一個沒有性別差異的世界。而男同志散文的整個認同歷程，無非就是一個期待能將自我認同從性卅別束縛中解放的深切盼望。
　　在慾望參與方面，臺灣當代男同志散文除了表現出鮮明的自戀傾向，它們也對姣好的男體進行摸索，它們藉著青春與肉體的描繪，或透過幻想與記憶來回味，或記述衣不蔽體的場面以意淫。城市與網路世界中繽紛的慾望也在男同志散文書寫的題材之列，男同志散文書寫的慾望大膽而且赤裸，情感熱切而且愛現，直接坦白地將情感盡洩而出。在其內心深處，它們所追求的其實更是一種對親密依靠與心靈慰藉的想望。在散文書寫的慾望世界裡，臺灣當代男同志散文的確沒有缺席，它們以坦誠的表白作為一次次參與，在臺灣當代散文的脈絡中別具直接、大膽的特色。
　　男同志在愛慾追索與身分（被）認同上所必須承擔的壓力，比起大多數異性戀的人的確更為沈重。在臺灣當代男同志散文中，不難發現它們往往藉著對自由的想像──植物的生機與飛行的想像──作為比擬與寄託與心靈慰藉，樂觀地面對這些沈重的壓力，並藉之寄託心中對自由的嚮往。它們企圖從精神上獲得超脫，並運用自己的想像力創造出樂園的世界，不僅補足了心靈的怨憾與沈重，亦隱然勾勒出一個「不寂寞」的樂園。




														英文摘要
													

The thesis aims to investigate gay essays in contemporary Taiwan. It examines gender identity, depiction of desire, and spiritual sustenance in these essays, appreciating the beauty and sadness in them.
　　In terms of gender identity, three phases can be found in the essays: call for gender identity, consideration of coming out, and real actions against stigmatization. The essays not only criticize the phallocentrism and natalism of heterosexuality, but also claim that gay groups should have the courage to actively position themselves in society. The inseparable stigmatization has gradually been bred due to misunderstanding about gays in society. However, depiction of and argument over stigmatization are rarely seen in the essays, and writers’ focuses are merely on transvestite and AIDS. In the essays, gender identity represents an attitude toward gays. It is only when gays can enjoy their sexual identity and meet their sexual desire without being particularly labeled as gays that the society is deemed one with gender equality. Gays’ pursuit of identity and recognition represents nothing more than a desire to free self identity from the constraints of genders.
　　In terms of the depiction of desire, apart from displaying obvious narcissism, gay essays in contemporary Taiwan also explore the beauty of male bodies. They reveal human desires and recollect fantasies and memories through depiction of youthfulness, bodies, and naked scenes. Colorful desire in cities or on the Internet also serves as a subject matter in the genre. The essays tend to depict desire boldly and directly, revealing intense love in a showy and direct manner. At their core, they pursue intimate support and spiritual consolation. Joining other kinds of essay writings, the essays also depict desire, but in a direct and sincere manner. With directness and boldness as their characteristics, they have established their position in the context of contemporary Taiwanese essays.
　　In the pursuit of love, desire, and self identity (or recognition from others), gays certainly face more pressure than most heterosexuals. Imagination of freedom—liveliness of plants and fantasy of flying—are often used as metaphors, spiritual sustenance, or spiritual consolation in gay essays 　　in contemporary Taiwan. In ding so, writers face heavy burdens optimistically as well as show their yearning for freedom. They aim to be spiritually unburdened, and they exert their imagination to create a paradise. The result is that they not only free themselves from spiritual resentment, regret, and heaviness, but implicitly outline a paradise without loneliness.




